; **********************************************************************************
; Regression test for card maize-42: programs larger than one 256-byte block, and
; control flow that crosses a block boundary.
;
; hello.bin is exactly 256 bytes (one block), the only reason the block-boundary bug
; went unnoticed. Code is emitted contiguously from address 0, so the two NOP sleds
; below place real, executable instructions on both sides of the 0x100 and 0x200
; boundaries. NOP is a single-byte opcode (0xAA).
;
; This proves:
;   - straight-line execution flows across the 0x100 boundary (sled 1 runs from
;     address 0 contiguously past 0x100 with no branch), and
;   - a JMP crosses the 0x200 boundary (the forward jump lands at stage_b, which the
;     filler sled 2 pushes past address 0x200).
;
; The image is > 256 bytes, so it also exercises multi-block serialization (mazm) and
; loading (maize). A green result requires the sled-1 marker (R0.B0 = 1) to have been
; executed, which can only happen if straight-line flow crossed 0x100 correctly.
; **********************************************************************************

$0000`0000:
    ; ---- sled 1: straight-line NOP run from address 0 across the 0x100 boundary ----
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
    NOP
